                <note type="abstract">The author argues that ʿAmmār mainly employs reductio ad absurdum arguments to render void the allegation of falsification of the Gospels (taḥrīf). His arguments display a “post-Enlightenment quality” in that he appeals to psychology and historicity. ʿAmmār deals with both the charges of alteration (taḥrīf al-naṣṣ) and misinterpretation (taḥrīf al-maʿnā). According to the author, the former was the more pressing issue. Al-Qāsim ibn Ibrāhīm’s Refutation of the Christians is used as a Muslim comparative text to ʿAmmār.</note>
